sections.english:
Monks, there are these six impossible conditions. Which six?
An individual endowed with right view cannot affirm that pleasure and pain are self-made;
an individual endowed with right view cannot affirm that pleasure and pain are made by another;
an individual endowed with right view cannot affirm that pleasure and pain are made both by oneself and by another;
an individual endowed with right view cannot affirm that pleasure and pain are not made by oneself, but arisen by chance;
an individual endowed with right view cannot affirm that pleasure and pain are not made by another, but arisen by chance;
an individual endowed with right view cannot affirm that pleasure and pain are not made by oneself and not made by another, but arisen by chance.

Why is that? Because, monks, for an individual endowed with right view, the cause is clearly seen, and the phenomena arisen from a cause are also clearly seen. These, monks, are the six impossible conditions.
